{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JqV5UkQEmyU6vNPx8w6ERG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Let me outline my analysis and proposed changes for each failure.\n\n**Failure 1: KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA → `UuIw`**\n\nTwo bugs:\n- Bug A: `/ Jesien / Zupy` at position 0 triggers the bilingual layout detection. It's a breadcrumb with ` / ` separators, not a title. The pipe filter catches ` | ` but not ` / `. The layout-based bilingual detection (Method 2 at line 517) fires because:\n  - prePos0 = `/ Jesien / Zupy` (mixed-case at position 0)\n  - nearbyAllCaps includes `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA` (position 1, ALL_CAPS)\n  - No word overlap between the two → classified as bilingual → title suppressed\n\n  Fix: Filter lines containing ` / ` as breadcrumbs (like the existing ` | ` filter), OR make the bilingual detection smarter about recognizing breadcrumbs.\n\n- Bug B: `UuIw` passes garbled check because it has 4 letters (threshold is ≤3). I need to increase the garbled threshold for single-word candidates or add a pattern to catch mixed-case gibberish like this.\n\nNow looking at another failure case: `MAKES 25 LABANEH BALLS` where the metadata filter catches `MAKES 25 LABANEH` but leaves `BALLS` as a standalone fragment that then eliminates the full title during dedup. I should either suppress short ALL_CAPS fragments that follow a filtered metadata line, or prevent very short words from outcompeting much longer candidates in the dedup logic. I need to trace through the capsCoalesced logic more carefully. When it processes the lines around \"MAKES 25 LABANEH\", I should check whether that line itself is all caps and whether \"BALLS\" on the next line would get merged into a coalesced group with other short all-caps lines nearby. the full `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` enters at position 0 from the coalesced caps, and the dedup logic kills the longer one since `\"labaneh balls with nigella seeds\"` contains `\"balls\"`. I need to fix this so orphaned metadata fragments don't get wrongly deduplicated — either by reversing the dedup direction when a short fragment like `BALLS` is being compared against a much longer, multi-word candidate, or by filtering out metadata continuation lines before they even enter the candidate pool.\n\nThe root problem is that `BALLS` shouldn't be a candidate at all since it's just the orphaned tail of a metadata line, so targeting that source makes more sense than patching the dedup logic itself. I'm thinking the cleanest solution is to handle multi-line metadata patterns during candidate generation — when a line like \"MAKES 25 LABANEH\" is flagged as metadata, I should also check if the next line is a short, all-caps continuation that completes the phrase, and filter both lines together rather than letting a stray word at a distant position override an earlier multi-word match. I'm leaning toward option 1—suppressing the next line if it's a short ALL_CAPS fragment right after a filtered metadata line. That feels cleaner than adding fragile exceptions to the word list. Now looking at the Polish recipe failure where OCR turned `DLA 4 OSÓB` into `DLA & OSOB`, bypassing the metadata filter because it expects a digit. I need to broaden that pattern to catch these OCR artifacts too. Refining the regex pattern to catch `DLA` followed by any characters and then `OSOB`/`OSÓB`/`PORCJ` — this handles OCR corruption while avoiding false positives on legitimate Polish recipe titles that might start with \"DLA\" (meaning \"for\").\n\nNow for the breadcrumb issue: the line starts with `/` and contains ` / ` which is clearly navigation, not content. The hard filter already blocks pipes, so I could add a check for leading slashes or ` / ` separators, but that risks catching legitimate recipe titles with slashes like ingredient alternatives. I need to be more surgical about this.\n\nLooking at the actual patterns, `/ Jesien / Zupy` has multiple slash-separated segments which screams breadcrumb, while continuation lines like `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` only have one segment after the slash. So the real distinguisher is whether there are multiple ` / ` separators in the line—that's the breadcrumb signature I should filter on. So I need to verify that `/ Jesien / Zupy` actually passes the hard filters. Tracing through: it's 16 characters, not an ingredient, doesn't start with a number or metadata, has decent vowel distribution so it's not garbled, and isn't a bullet point or pipe separator. The key insight is that it has two slashes, which my breadcrumb detection should catch as a multi-segment path rather than a title.\n\nThe fix is to add a check for lines starting with `/` followed by whitespace, since those are continuation markers that shouldn't be treated as standalone entries. I'm considering a regex like checking if the trimmed text starts with `/ ` to filter these out before they pass the hard filters. Checking the split approach — if I divide by `/`, a breadcrumb like `/ Jesien / Zupy` gives me three parts, while a single-slash title like `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` gives me two. So filtering for `split('/').length >= 3` catches the breadcrumbs without removing legitimate recipe titles with one slash. In practice, recipe titles don't really use `/` as a way to list alternatives—they'd say \"and\" or \"or\" instead. The `/` pattern is more of a navigation breadcrumb thing. So filtering out titles with 2+ slashes should be safe without losing real recipes.\n\nFor the bilingual detection, I could also prevent breadcrumb-style titles from being treated as valid candidates in the first place, but filtering them outright is cleaner.\n\nNow looking at Bug B with `UuIw`—I need to catch single-word candidates with that kind of garbled mixed casing. The simplest fix is to lower the single-word garbled threshold from 3 letters down to 4, which would catch this case.\n\nBut that's risky because it might filter out legitimate short recipe titles like \"Cake\" or \"Soup\". A better approach is to detect impossible casing patterns directly—checking for lowercase letters followed by uppercase ones in the middle of a word, which wouldn't happen in normal title case. That pattern would catch `UuIw` but let \"Cake\" through.\n\nI'm concerned about edge cases like \"iPhone\" or \"McDonald's\" that have mid-word capitals, but those wouldn't appear as recipe titles anyway, and the test cases all use standard casing, so this should be safe. Let me draft the implementation plan now.\n\nI'll tackle three specific failures: first, add a hard filter to reject lines with multiple slashes to catch breadcrumb navigation like `/ Jesien / Zupy`. Second, detect garbled text by flagging single words with internal lowercase-to-uppercase transitions, which catches OCR noise like `UuIw`. Third, after filtering metadata, suppress short ALL_CAPS fragments that are likely continuations of the filtered line, either by suppressing the next line or extending the sub-section header filter to catch these fragments.\n\nFor the metadata continuation issue, I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to add a filter in the candidate-building stage that treats short ALL_CAPS fragments following metadata as contaminated and excludes them. But since `passesHardFilters` doesn't have context about neighboring lines, this needs to happen at a higher level. A more general fix would be to modify the dedup logic to prevent a single word from eliminating a candidate with significantly more words—this addresses the root cause that fragments shouldn't destroy well-formed titles. The most surgical approach is to add a pre-dedup step that protects against this specific case.\n\nLooking at the existing pre-dedup filter, it already checks for sub-section headers by examining what follows them, but `BALLS` at position 13 isn't a sub-section header—it's just an orphaned metadata fragment that happens to pass the current checks. I need to reconsider the filtering logic from a different angle.\n\nThe real problem is that metadata can span multiple source lines, like `MAKES 25 LABANEH` followed by `BALLS`, but the capsCoalesced step can't merge them because the first line exceeds the word limit. So I need to track which lines fail the metadata check and then suppress any short ALL_CAPS fragments that immediately follow them.\n\nBuilding a set of metadata continuation positions...\n\nActually, let me trace through what happens with `MAKES 25 LABANEH` — it's three words so capsCoalesced won't merge it, and `BALLS` doesn't match the continuation pattern either, so they stay separate in mergedLines. When I run `MAKES 25 LABANEH` through `passesHardFilters` and check if it looks like metadata, I need to see what that function returns.\n\nLooking at the logic, `MAKES 25 LABANEH` matches the metadata pattern for recipe yields, so it gets filtered out. But then `BALLS` comes next and passes all the filters, so it ends up in the candidate pool even though it's probably meant to be part of that metadata line. I need to track when a line is filtered as metadata and suppress the following short line if it looks like a continuation — I can do this by adding a flag that skips the next iteration when we detect this pattern.\n\nActually, there's a simpler approach: instead of modifying the candidate loop, I could change the deduplication logic to use word-boundary matching rather than substring matching, so `BALLS` wouldn't be considered a duplicate of `LABANEH` just because it appears within it.\n\nBut wait—`BALLS` is actually a complete word within `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`, so that wouldn't solve the problem either.\n\nI think the metadata continuation approach is the right call. It directly addresses the root cause rather than trying to patch the dedup logic. Looking at the three failure modes I've identified, they're fairly independent issues, so I'll need targeted fixes for each rather than one catch-all solution.\n\nNow let me draft the improvement plan.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6071,"cache_read_input_tokens":53363,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6071},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"beba072c-8756-4212-892f-70153dbd85fa","uuid":"d017f2bc-3f4a-4c5d-88fc-b684b7498a99"}
